{"source_key":"sha256-9b0f9c3f961abf38b897cbefe7e9ac46","record_index":79,"record_hash":"sha256:9f1687b29ac8af09f05900714e297818fbc61ad80a7ae9de153a97d322415bfe","timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:50:27.671Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: bb5543\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1650\nOutput:\n     1\t# Future Use Cases\n     2\t\n     3\tThis document records the product direction the first agentlog POC should point\n     4\ttoward. These use cases are not implemented end to end by the POC, but they\n     5\tshape the data model.\n     6\t\n     7\t## 1. Session Handoff\n     8\t\n     9\tA developer starts an agent session on one machine and wants to continue it on\n    10\tanother machine, possibly with another agent.\n    11\t\n    12\tExamples:\n    13\t\n    14\t- Claude Code starts the planning locally, then OpenClaw continues on a remote\n    15\t  machine where the repository is already available.\n    16\t- OpenClaw starts work on a remote machine, then the user continues locally so\n    17\t  they can run a desktop app or device-specific tests.\n    18\t\n    19\tFor this to work later, GitButler needs to capture enough session context into\n    20\tGitMeta, move that metadata through Git transport, and expose it on the other\n    21\tside in a form that another agent can use. The POC does not serialize, push,\n    22\tfetch, or resume a session, but its project-scoped session records should be\n    23\tdurable enough to make that possible.\n    24\t\n    25\tExpected access pattern:\n    26\t\n    27\t1. fetch or otherwise exchange GitMeta data for the repository\n    28\t2. read `gitbutler:agent-sessions` from the `project` target\n    29\t3. choose a session, either by recency, user selection, or a future explicit\n    30\t   relationship\n    31\t4. read `gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript`\n    32\t5. reconstruct useful context from `kind`, `role`, `text`, `tool_name`,\n    33\t   `tool_input`, `source_event_kind`, and redacted `source_record`\n    34\t6. sort records by transcript fields rather than relying on stored GitMeta list\n    35\t   order\n    36\t\n    37\tThat means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\n    38\tmachine's file paths, working-directory state, branch state, or raw provider\n    39\tse\n[TRUNCATED]\n    99\t\n   100\t```text\n   101\tsession 1\n   102\t  -> feature branch\n   103\t  -> bugfix branch\n   104\t```\n   105\t\n   106\tThe durable object should therefore be the project-scoped GitButler agent\n   107\tsession. Branches, commits, changes, and pull requests should later reference\n   108\tsession keys rather than own the transcript data directly.\n   109\t\n   110\tThis is especially important for GitButler because a single worktree may contain\n   111\tmultiple active branches at once. An agent can produce edits that the user later\n   112\tsplits across several branches, so the capture layer should not guess ownership\n   113\tfrom the current branch.\n   114\t\n   115\tRelationship keys can look like this:\n   116\t\n   117\t```text\n   118\t<branch/change/commit target>\n   119\t  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n   120\t```\n   121\t\n   122\tThat shape supports:\n   123\t\n   124\t- sessions that exist before code is written\n   125\t- one session associated with many branch or review objects\n   126\t- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n   127\t- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n   128\t\n   129\t## POC Direction\n   130\t\n   131\tThe first POC should:\n   132\t\n   133\t- write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n   134\t- keep session data on the `project` target\n   135\t- allow optional explicit target association without inference\n   136\t- use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n   137\t- keep source metadata separate from per-record transcript records\n   138\t- keep enough normalized fields to support timeline browsing without reparsing\n   139\t  every provider-specific record\n   140\t- avoid storing local paths, working-directory values, branches, or raw provider\n   141\t  session ids\n   142\t- avoid serialization, push, fetch, sync, branch inference, and automatic PR\n   143\t  association\n   144\t\n   145\tThe POC should not try to solve session merging. A future UX can decide whether\n   146\tmultiple provider sessions should be joined into one GitButler-level session.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:50:27.671Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}